{"title_page": "Seal Island (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1948 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Seal Island\n| image          = Seal Island.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster for ''Seal Island''\n| director       = [[James Algar]]\n| producer       = [[Ben Sharpsteen]]<br>[[Walt Disney]]\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = [[Winston Hibler]]\n| music          = [[Oliver Wallace]]\n| cinematography = Alfred Milotte\n| editing        = Anthony Gerard\n| studio         = [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[RKO Pictures|RKO Radio Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1948|12|21}}\n| runtime        = 27 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Seal Island''''' is a 1948 American [[documentary film]] directed by [[James Algar]]. Produced by [[Walt Disney]], it was the first installment of the ''[[True-Life Adventures]]'' series of nature documentaries. It won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in [[21st Academy Awards|1949]] for [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Short Subject (Two-Reel)]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/141404/Seal-Island/details |title=New York Times: Seal Island |accessdate=May 18, 2008|work=NY Times}}</ref>{{dead link|date=May 2019}}<ref name=\"Oscars1949\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1949 |title=The 21st Academy Awards (1949) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 29, 2019 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]])}}</ref> \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Winston Hibler]] as Narrator\n\n==Production==\nIn 1947, Walt Disney contracted with Alfred and Elma Milotte to shoot documentary footage of the wildlife and culture of [[Alaska]]. Disney did not see the theatrical value in the footage of human activity in Alaska, but he was intrigued with footage that the Milottes shot of the seal population at the [[Pribilof Islands]]. Disney himself coined the title ''Seal Island'' for the film, and planned it as the first in a new series of nature documentaries called [[True-Life Adventures]].<ref name=WD>{{Cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/waltdisneyameric00thom/page/213 | title=Walt Disney: An American Original | author=Bob Thomas | publisher=Simon & Schuster/Pocket Books | pages=[https://archive.org/details/waltdisneyameric00thom/page/213 213\u20134] | year=1976 | isbn=0-671-66232-5 }}</ref>\n\nThe Milottes shot more than 100,000 feet of film and spent over a year filming the seals. The total production cost Disney a little over $100,000.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41e-Ru0wRkEC&pg=PA446&dq=%22seal+island%22+disney&ei=O_7kSpazEoKCzgS2kKGTDA#v=onepage&q=%22seal%20island%22%20disney&f=false | title=Walt Disney: The Triumph of the American Imagination |author=Neal Gabler | publisher=Random House | pages=444\u20135 | year=2007 | isbn=0-679-75747-3}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[RKO Pictures]], the studio distributing Disney's films at the time, initially refused to release the half-hour ''Seal Island''.  Disney booked the film for its [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City|New York]] theatrical engagements, and RKO agreed to release the film nationally only after it proved its commercial potential and received the Academy Award.<ref name=WD/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0040763|title=Seal Island}}\n\n{{True Life Adventures}}\n{{AcademyAwardBestShort 1941-1960}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seal Island}}\n[[Category:1948 films]]\n[[Category:1940s documentary films]]\n[[Category:1948 short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white documentary films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Disney documentary films]]\n[[Category:Disney short films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nature]]\n[[Category:Films set in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films about mammals]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Oliver Wallace]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Algar]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Walt Disney]]\n[[Category:Live Action Short Film Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Pribilof Islands]]\n[[Category:Pinnipeds]]\n[[Category:Short documentary films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1948 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Seal Island\n| image          = Seal Island.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster for ''Seal Island''\n| director       = [[James Algar]]\n| producer       = [[Ben Sharpsteen]]<br>[[Walt Disney]]\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = [[Winston Hibler]]\n| music          = [[Oliver Wallace]]\n| cinematography = Alfred Milotte\n| editing        = Anthony Gerard\n| studio         = [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[RKO Pictures|RKO Radio Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1948|12|21}}\n| runtime        = 27 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Seal Island''''' is a 1948 American [[documentary film]] directed by [[James Algar]]. Produced by [[Walt Disney]], it was the first installment of the ''[[True-Life Adventures]]'' series of nature documentaries. It won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in [[21st Academy Awards|1949]] for [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Short Subject (Two-Reel)]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/141404/Seal-Island/details |title=New York Times: Seal Island |accessdate=May 18, 2008|work=NY Times}}</ref>{{dead link|date=May 2019}}<ref name=\"Oscars1949\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1949 |title=The 21st Academy Awards (1949) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 29, 2019 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]])}}</ref> \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Winston Hibler]] as Narrator\n\n==Production==\nIn 1947, Walt Disney contracted with Alfred and Elma Milotte to shoot documentary footage of the wildlife and culture of [[Alaska]]. Disney did not see the theatrical value in the footage of human activity in Alaska, but he was intrigued with footage that the Milottes shot of the seal population at the [[Pribilof Islands]]. Disney himself coined the title ''Seal Island'' for the film, and planned it as the first in a new series of nature documentaries called [[True-Life Adventures]].<ref name=WD>{{Cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/waltdisneyameric00thom/page/213 | title=Walt Disney: An American Original | author=Bob Thomas | publisher=Simon & Schuster/Pocket Books | pages=[https://archive.org/details/waltdisneyameric00thom/page/213 213\u20134] | year=1976 | isbn=0-671-66232-5 }}</ref>\n\nThe Milottes shot more than 100,000 feet of film and spent over a year filming the seals. The total production cost Disney a little over $100,000.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41e-Ru0wRkEC&pg=PA446&dq=%22seal+island%22+disney&ei=O_7kSpazEoKCzgS2kKGTDA#v=onepage&q=%22seal%20island%22%20disney&f=false | title=Walt Disney: The Triumph of the American Imagination |author=Neal Gabler | publisher=Random House | pages=444\u20135 | year=2007 | isbn=0-679-75747-3}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[RKO Pictures]], the studio distributing Disney's films at the time, initially refused to release the half-hour ''Seal Island''.  Disney booked the film for its [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City|New York]] theatrical engagements, and RKO agreed to release the film nationally only after it proved its commercial potential and received the Academy Award.<ref name=WD/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0040763|title=Seal Island}}\n\n{{True Life Adventures}}\n{{AcademyAwardBestShort 1941-1960}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seal Island}}\n[[Category:1948 films]]\n[[Category:1940s documentary films]]\n[[Category:1948 short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white documentary films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Disney documentary films]]\n[[Category:Disney short films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about nature]]\n[[Category:Films set in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films about mammals]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Oliver Wallace]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Algar]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Walt Disney]]\n[[Category:Live Action Short Film Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Pribilof Islands]]\n[[Category:Pinnipeds]]\n[[Category:Short documentary films]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seal_Island_(film)"}
